
POSTMARITAL RESIDENCE PRACTICE IN SOUTHERN BRAZILIAN 
COASTAL GROUPS: CONT INUITY AND CHANGE 

Mark Hubbe, Walter Alves Neves, Emiliano Castro de Oliveira and Andre Strauss 
The coastal plains of the States of Pa rand and Santa Catarina, in Southern Brazil, were first settled around 6000 B.P. by she I/mound builders, a successful fisher-hunter-gatherer population that inhabited the coastal lowlands practically unchanged for almost five thousand years. Shel/mounds were typically occupied as residential sites as well as cemeteries, and are usu­ally associated with rich alimentary zones. Around 1200 B.P., the first evidence of ceramics brought from the interior is found in coastal areas, and together with ceramics there is a progressive abandonment of shellmound construction in favor of flat and shallow sites. Here we consider if these changes were reflected in the postmarital residence practice of coastal groups, i.e., if the arrival or intensification of contact with groups from the interior resulted in changes in this aspect of social structure among the coastal groups. To test the postmarital residence practice we analyzed within-group variability ratios between males and females, following previous studies on the topic, and between-group correlations between Maha­lanobis distances and geographic distances. The results suggest that in the pre-ceramic series a matrilocal, postmarital res­idential system predominated, while in the ceramic period there was a shift toward patrilocality. This favors the hypothesis that the changes experienced by coastal groups after 1200 B.P. affected not only their economy and material culture, but important aspects of their sociopolitical organization as well. 
Las planicies costeras de Los Estados de Paranti y de Santa Catarina, en el Sur de Brasil, fueron colonizadas hace aproxi­madamente 6000 A.P. por grupos pescadores-cazadores-recolectores cuya manifestaci6n material mas evidente son los sitios conchales (sambaquis), que fueron ocupados como sitios habitacionales y cementerios. Los constructores de conchales fueron grupos que ocuparon exitosamente regiones de alta productividad de recursos alimenticios, habitando la region de manera estab/e e ininterrumpida por casi 5000 aiios. Las primeras evidencias de certimica asociada a sitios costeros ocurren alrede­dor de 1200 A.P. y su presencia en esta zona estti asociada al abandono gradual de la prtictica de construir conchales. En este trabajo se estudia si la llegada de la certimica a la costa de Paranti y de Santa Catarina Jue acompaiiada por cambios en la prtictica de residencia post-marital de los grupos costeros, o sea, si la llegada de grupos del interior ylo la intensificaci6n de! contacto con grupos de! interior result6 en cambios en este aspecto de la estructura social de los grupos que habitaron las p/anicies costeras. El patron de residencia post-marital de grupos pre-certimicos y certimicos fue estimado a traves del antili­sis de la variabilidad morfol6gica intra-grupo para cada sexo, siguiendo estudios anteriores, y de la correlaci6n entre matri­ces de distancias de Mahalanobis para cada sexo y la distancia geogrtifica entre los sitios. Los resultados de ambos antilisis sugieren que, entre los grupos pre-certimicos, predominaba un sistema matrilocal, mientras que en el periodo certimico ocur­ri6 un cambio orientado a la patrilocalidad. Estos resultados favorecen la hip6tesis de que los cambios experimentados por los grupos costeros despues de 1200 A.P. afectaron no solamente su econom{a y cultura material, sino tambien importantes aspectos de su organizaci6n sociopolftica. 

